<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is the exposure triangle?", answer: "The exposure triangle consists of three camera settings that control how much light reaches the sensor: aperture (f-stop), shutter speed, and ISO sensitivity. Changing one setting requires adjusting at least one of the others to maintain the same overall exposure." },
  { question: "What is an exposure value (EV)?", answer: "Exposure value (EV) is a number that represents a combination of aperture and shutter speed at a given ISO. Each whole EV step doubles or halves the amount of light. EV is calculated as log2(N^2/t) where N is the f-number and t is the shutter speed in seconds." },
  { question: "How do I calculate equivalent exposures?", answer: "If you change one exposure setting by a certain number of stops, compensate by changing another setting by the same number of stops in the opposite direction. For example, opening the aperture by 1 stop (f/5.6 to f/4) requires doubling the shutter speed (1/125s to 1/250s) to maintain the same exposure." },
  { question: "What is a stop in photography?", answer: "A stop is a doubling or halving of the amount of light. One stop more light means twice as much light; one stop less means half. Aperture stops follow the sequence f/1, f/1.4, f/2, f/2.8, f/4, f/5.6, f/8, f/11, f/16, f/22. ISO and shutter speed double or halve per stop." },
  { question: "How does ISO affect image quality?", answer: "Higher ISO values amplify the sensor signal, which brightens the image but also amplifies noise. Lower ISO values (100-400) produce the cleanest images. Modern cameras handle high ISO well, but image quality degrades progressively above ISO 3200-6400 on most cameras." }
]) %>

